@node not15 "3DFX FOR AMIGA: TO BE OR NOT TO BE"

@{B}3DFX@{UB} FOR @{B}AMIGA@{UB}: TO BE OR NOT TO BE
----------------------------------

From: @{I}sam jordan@{UI} @{I}jordsamo@htlchur.ch@{UI}@{UI}

Hi

This  newsletter  is  intended  to  be  written for all those @{B}AMIGA@{UB} users, which
really  care  for  the future of the @{B}AMIGA@{UB}, especially concerning games. I would
like to show anyone what we can expect in future, what will be possible and what
the  @{B}AMIGA@{UB}  users themselves have to contribute to make all this possible. Now a
very  important  decision  is  to  be  done,  which  will  influence  the future
development  of  @{B}AMIGA@{UB}  games, and how the decision will look like, depends very
much on the @{B}AMIGA@{UB} users themselves.

In  the  past  weeks  there  were  a  lot of discussions about the @{B}Villagetronic@{UB}
project,  which  is supposed to bring the @{B}Voodoo1@{UB} hardware for @{B}AMIGA@{UB}. I will now
explain,  what  this  project means for the potential customers and what it will
mean for the @{B}AMIGA@{UB} as a whole.

First,  for  all  those, who spreaded wrong information:@{B}Villagetronic@{UB} still need
pre-orders! The decision about the project will be done in a few weeks, so there
is  not  much time left. If they don't get the expected 500 preorders, they will
definitely  cancel  the  project.  Pre-orders  can  be done on the @{B}villagetronic@{UB}
websites.

I'm  sure  that  there are a lot of people around, which might be interested for
such  a  hardware,  but which fear, that this hardware will become as useless as
all  other  3D  graphics board up to now. The reason for this lack of supporting
software  were the missing 3D drivers (a situation which is unthinkable on other
platforms,  where the chip manufacturers themselves provide appropriate drivers,
most often with support for @{B}Direct3D@{UB} and @{B}OpenGL@{UB}).

The  same  is now coming for the @{B}AMIGA@{UB}, the @{B}Warp3D@{UB} driver system intends to give
the  programmers  an instrument in their hands to be able to use the advanced 3D
features.  Its  API  is  hardware-independent,  so  that any 3D hardware will be
supported  for @{B}AMIGA@{UB}. The @{B}Virge@{UB} driver is done, the @{B}Permedia2@{UB} driver in work and
any  other  driver will be written, so that every new 3D hardware will come with
complete  drivers  and software using them (and the drivers will be there at the
first  release  of  the  hardware,  not  months  or even years later!). The @{B}3dfx@{UB}
hardware will be definitely supported by @{B}Warp3D@{UB}.

With  the  first  release  of  @{B}Warp3D@{UB} (coming this or next week) there will be a
release  of  the  first game supporting @{B}Warp3D@{UB}: @{B}ADescent@{UB}. This game demonstrates
the  features  and performance of 3D hardware and shows that it is even possible
to  play  games  fast  with  fast @{B}68K@{UB} processors. The difference between the new
@{B}Warp3D-Descent@{UB} version and the previous version with @{B}Virge@{UB} support (through some
unfinished beta drivers) are:
   * The  @{B}W3D@{UB}  version supports any 3D hardware, while the old one only supports
     the @{B}Virge@{UB}
   * The  @{B}W3D@{UB}  version  runs  with  @{B}P96@{UB}  and  with  @{B}CGFX@{UB}, while the old one only
     supports @{B}CGFX@{UB}
   * The  @{B}W3D@{UB}  version has an extremly better graphics quality than the old one,
     because these old drivers were unfinished and didn't support many features,
     which  improve  the graphics quality a lot. The @{B}W3D@{UB} version provides on the
     @{B}Virge@{UB}  bilinear  filtering, mipmapping, trilinear filtering and fogging for
     top graphics quality.
   * The  @{B}W3D@{UB}  version  runs  much  faster then the old version, since the @{B}Virge@{UB}
     driver  for @{B}W3D@{UB} was optimized like hell (core parts of the setup stage were
     written  in  @{B}ASM@{UB}  for both CPU's). While @{B}Descent@{UB} is only playable nicely in
     resolutions  up  to 320*400*15 on the @{B}Virge@{UB}, it will be possible to play it
     in  800*600*15  on  a  @{B}Voodoo1@{UB}  card  at nice frame rate (and @{B}Descent@{UB} looks
     incredible at that resolution!)

This  feature  list  should  show,  what  it  means to have hardware-independent
drivers.  You  can  develop  a  software today and it will work with hardware of
tomorrow, without any single change of code.

Meanwhile  there  are  a  lot of developers which have access to the beta files,
which  partially  work for commercial game projects, so that we can expect a lot
of  applications  which support 3D hardware. The game company @{B}Digital Images@{UB} has
announced  support  for  @{B}Warp3D@{UB}  and  @{B}WarpUp@{UB}  and  they have some promising game
projects.  A  list  of those projects will be available on the 3DWorld web sites
soon.

As we all know, there were @{B}PC@{UB} games around which supported @{B}OpenGL@{UB} and achieved a
fantastic  graphics  quality, like @{B}Quake2@{UB}. There is a slight chance to get games
like  @{B}Quake2@{UB} for @{B}AMIGA@{UB}, but it is ABSOLUTELY NECESSARY to have *TOP* 3D hardware
available  to  run  such  games  fast enough. The @{B}Virge@{UB} has no chance to achieve
that,  while  the  @{B}Permedia2@{UB}  should give acceptable frame rates and the @{B}Voodoo1@{UB}
will fly.

@{B}OpenGL@{UB}  with  3D  hardware support is also coming to the @{B}AMIGA@{UB}. At the same time
with  @{B}Warp3D@{UB}  there  will  be  the  release  of @{B}StormMesa 3.0@{UB}, which supports 3D
hardware through @{B}Warp3D@{UB}. I demonstrated this at cologne, but the performance was
even improved very much meanwhile, through many optimizations. I spend very much
time  to  get  out  the  max.  of  @{B}OpenGL@{UB}  and 3D-hardware (by rewriting tons of
functions  to  ASM for both CPU's) and the results are very impressive even with
the @{B}Virge@{UB}.

@{B}StormMesa  3.0@{UB}  and  @{B}Warp3D@{UB} will be available for @{B}68K@{UB} and @{B}PPC@{UB}/@{B}WarpUp@{UB}, so that it
would  be  possible  to  play games like @{B}Quake2@{UB} in high resolutions at very high
speed.  Even  the @{B}Virge@{UB} accelerates those demos by several factors, so that real
good hardware can cause real miracles.

But  all  this  requires,  that  there  are  enough  users around with *FAST* 3D
hardware.  Games  like @{B}Quake2@{UB} and @{B}Wipeout@{UB} really need 3D hardware to run nicely,
so  all  these projects are in real danger, if there is not enough fast hardware
around.  Running an @{B}OpenGL@{UB} game on a plain @{B}PPC@{UB} without 3D hardware support means
the  same  as  playing  @{B}Quake1@{UB}  on  a  @{B}68040@{UB}  processor.  It is useless! And the
companies  will  also  come  to this conclusion, so they need the perspective to
sell enough copies of the game.

Please  note,  that  it is completely impossible to run 3D games on the @{B}AMIGA@{UB} in
high  resolutions  at high speed, if there is no 3D hardware present. To display
the  graphics  data,  it  has  to be transferred through the @{B}Z3@{UB} resp. @{B}CVPPC@{UB} bus,
which  is  dead  slow. The @{B}PowerPC@{UB} is really useless for these high resolutions.
The 3D hardware are the only chance to bypass this bottleneck.

To  come  to  the initial point: I strongly believe that the decision to make or
not to make the hardware has a *major* influence to the future game market. Many
promising  game  projects  are  announced, but only few of them will actually be
released,  because  the  other  ones  need more power than there actually is (in
terms of sold 3D graphics boards)

Just a question to all those people, which would like to buy those new announced
@{B}PPC@{UB}  boards:  what  serious 3D accelerator do you want to buy? There is a simple
answer:  there  is none. Except if the @{B}3DFX@{UB} overdrive is released. Let us have a
look at the other 3D chips available:
  * @{B}Virge@{UB}:  very  old,  very  weak  compared to modern 3D chips, only usable for
    custom engines and for low resolutions. Too weak for serious @{B}OpenGL@{UB} (serious
    means beeing able to achieve a good frame rate for complex applications like
    those games)
  * @{B}Permedia2@{UB}:  newer  than  the  @{B}Virge@{UB},  much faster, but restricted to be used
    together  with  the  @{B}Phase5@{UB} hardware (please forget the idea, that those new
    boards  will provide the @{B}CVPPC@{UB} slot, this won't be the case). And for those,
    which  might have a look at the crazy idea to run one of those @{B}Escena@{UB} boards
    in  parallel  to the @{B}CyberVisionPPC@{UB}: The Escena board will probably not have
    access  to  the @{B}CVPPC@{UB}, so the hardware could only be accessed via the @{B}68K@{UB} by
    trapping  the  accesses  and processing appropriate exception handlers. This
    means:  major  slowdown,  especially for 3D operations (it takes at least 10
    register  accesses  for  one  single triangle, and modern games draw several
    thousands of them per frame).

Now  it's  up  to  those  users,  which  didn't decide yet to pre-order the @{B}3dfx@{UB}
overdrive,  to do it *NOW*, because a few weeks later it will be too late (Note:
The  period  for  the pre-ordering will finnish on December, 20th). The hardware
will  be  released  together  with  complete  drivers, with @{B}OpenGL@{UB} support, with
several  hundreds  of @{B}OpenGL@{UB} demos, together with @{B}Descent@{UB} (executable only), and
all  game projects, which are now in the making with @{B}W3D@{UB} support, will instantly
work with the hardware.

To  all  others, which won't buy it because they don't own a @{B}PIV@{UB} or because they
already  have  another  accelerator:  please  talk  with  people  which might be
interested  in  this  hardware, tell them what I have written here. Also address
people  which  don't  have internet access, spread this message. All users which
pre-order  a  hardware  will get a top hardware together with tons of supporting
software  and  they  will  help  the  @{B}AMIGA@{UB}  very much, since they give the game
developers the sign, that it is really worth to support this technology.

Please  spread  this  message, display them everywhere, send it to every mailing
list,  talk about it, do all you can to support this fantastic project! Convinve
the  people  to  pre-order the hardware! By supporting the 3DFX project, you are
also  supporting  the  @{B}Warp3D@{UB} team, which spend incredible much time to give the
@{B}AMIGA@{UB} the possibility to run games at never-seen speed, and all that for free.

If you have some questions addressed to myself, then please write them to one of
the  eMail  addresses  below.  You  can  also  ask  all  members of the @{B}W3D@{UB} team
(@{I}Hans-Joerg@{UI} and @{I}Thomas Frieden@{UI}, and myself).

To be or not to be, that's now the question.

bye
--
