@node not34 "IAT MANUFACTURING TO DEVELOP AN AMIGA PARALLEL PROCESSING SYSTEM"

@{B}IAT MANUFACTURING@{UB} TO DEVELOP AN @{B}AMIGA@{UB} PARALLEL PROCESSING SYSTEM
----------------------------------------------------------------

Issued By: @{B}IAT Manufacturing@{UB}

This information is provided primarily for developers in the @{B}Amiga@{UB} community and
contains  information  on a product which is still very much under  development.
Any  specifications remain subject to change. This project has been underway for
a  number  of  months  and  is  now approaching hardware completion. The @{B}Impulse
Multiprocessing@{UB}  system  is  being  developed  jointly  by @{B}IAT Manufacturing@{UB} and
@{B}Alternate Approach@{UB}. @{B}Alternate Approach@{UB} are  handling the development of a custom
Micro-OS  which  will  enable transparent  integration with @{B}Amiga OS@{UB}® which does
not  currently support multiple  processors. @{B}IAT Manufacturing@{UB} is developing the
system  hardware  based    around @{B}Motorola@{UB}'s @{B}Coldfire@{UB} Family of Microprocessors.
Development of the Operating System component is underway.

@{I}Project Aims@{UI}

  * To provide a low cost alternative to other acceleration systems.
  * Provide instruction sets similar to the @{B}68k@{UB}.
  * Provide  a system which can be upgraded in the future whilst maintaining any
    existing functionality in addition to the upgrade.

@{I}Advantages of @{B}Impulse@{UB}@{UI}

 *  MODULAR system allows low cost production & easy upgrades
 *  Single  Board  production  unit  with  modular interface boards for specific
    machines,  e.g.,  you  install an impulse card on an @{B}A1200@{UB}, when you upgrade
    you only need to change the interface board, not the whole system.
 *  The  system  is  ideally  suited  to  a  truly multitasking environment, the
    individual  processors  can  work on different tasks; reducing the number of
    context switches, interrupts from expansion cards could also be serviced via
    external request pins.

@{I}Specifications@{UI}

These  specifications  are  preliminary,  but are unlikely to change in the near
future. The first board designs utilise the @{B}MCF5307@{UB} processors working in tandem
with  a  @{B}68k@{UB},  all  processors  are  autonomous  (this  is  not  a  co-processor
arrangement).  The  product  makes full use of multiple buses to minimise use of
the  main  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  bus  (@{B}IMultibus@{UB}© technology). If this product is successful we
plan  to  move  towards @{B}V4 Coldfire@{UB}® during 1999 with low cost 600MIPS solutions
(and  no  @{B}68k@{UB}'s in sight). Theoretically there is also no reason why the @{B}Impulse@{UB}
system  could not function alongside a @{B}PPC@{UB} card. Why @{B}Coldfire@{UB}? We have chosen to
use  the @{B}ColdFire@{UB} range for a number of reasons, the most obvious being the fact
that  it is highly compatible with @{B}68k@{UB} code. The @{B}ColdFire@{UB} range has recently had
frequent  updates  and  has  a  development roadmap taking it well into the next
millennium.  Because  the @{B}CF@{UB} is Variable-length @{B}RISC@{UB} instructions are denser and
less  memory  is required to run the same applications also the @{B}CF@{UB} does more per
MIP  than conventional @{B}RISC@{UB}. The Fact that the @{B}ColdFire@{UB} range is low cost allows
us  to  build  multiple  processor  systems  which  are  more  responsive than a
conventional  single  processor  setup.  The  @{B}MCF5307@{UB} used in our first units is
typical   of   the  @{B}ColdFire@{UB}  architecture  with  each  device  having  on-board
peripherals  and  memory  as  well  as  large  caches. @{B}DSP@{UB} functionality is also
introduced by the @{B}ColdFire MAC@{UB} (multiply-accumulate) unit.

@{I}Planned specification includes:@{UI}

   * Two @{B}MCF5307@{UB} processors (70 MIPS each) + @{B}68k@{UB} processor
   * Two Fully functional FPU's
   * 8 megabit SRAM (2-clock - 12ns access time)
   * Three RS232 type serial ports
   * M-bus Support (Compatibility with I2C standard)
   * Custom  Expansion  Bus  with  access  to  programmable  chip  selects & DMA
     controller
   * Standard DRAM controllers
   * 4 General-Purpose Timers The Future?

The  @{B}ColdFire@{UB}  range  is well suited to use in a multimedia environment; this is
shown  by the wealth of available third party companion IC's available including
Ethernet  and @{B}PCI@{UB} interfaces. @{B}IAT Manufacturing@{UB} plans to continue development of
the  @{B}Impulse@{UB} range to provide low cost and customisable acceleration options for
the  future.  @{B}Impulse@{UB}  delivers our unique @{B}IBus@{UB}© interface which provides a very
low  cost  solution  for  third  party peripheral products giving access to Chip
selects multiple busses & 2 @{B}CF@{UB} Parallel ports. The @{B}5307@{UB}'s two-wire I2C interface
could open up new possibilities in terms of peripheral connection.

@{I}Availability@{UI}
The  system  is still under development but release in early 1999 is a realistic
prospect. Distribution will be handled By @{B}Blittersoft LTD@{UB}.

@{I}Contact@{UI}
Developers  should  contact @{B}IAT Manufacturing@{UB} project co-ordinator @{I}D.S Tarmey@{UI} at
if  you  have  any  further questions. We are quite busy at the present time but
will  endeavour  to  reply  to  your  mails ASAP. This text is not intended as a
formative  product  evaluation,  its  details are as accurate as possible at the
time of release. This is classed as developer information.

